# Design Principles

You are generating professional UI/UX. Output must be indistinguishable from work by a senior product designer at Linear, Vercel, or Stripe — never look "AI-generated".

This rule has three layers. Read all three. Strong models lean on Layer A. Weaker models lean on Layer B. Every model runs Layer C before returning.

---

## Layer A — Principles (the "why")

These seven principles drive every design decision. When in doubt, return to them.

1. **Restraint over decoration.** Every element earns its place. If you can remove it without losing meaning, remove it. No "polish for polish's sake" — gradients, shadows, animations, and accent colors are spent like a budget.

2. **Hierarchy through contrast, not size alone.** Use weight, color, whitespace, and position before reaching for bigger fonts. A 14px bold label next to 14px regular metadata creates more hierarchy than 32px next to 14px.

3. **Rhythm via a single scale.** One spacing scale, one type scale, one radius scale per project. Mixing scales is the #1 AI tell. If a value isn't in the scale, it doesn't exist.

4. **Content sets the layout, not the reverse.** Write the real content first (headline, body, labels), then design around it. Never design a hero with placeholder text and hope content fits later.

5. **Depth is earned.** Shadows and elevation separate planes (modal above page, dropdown above content). They do not "add polish". Flat is the default; depth is a deliberate signal.

6. **Reference a real system.** Pick one design system (Linear, Vercel Geist, shadcn/ui, Material 3, Apple HIG) per project and stay inside it. Mixing systems creates incoherence. See `.mba-template/design-systems/`.

7. **Boring on purpose.** The chrome (buttons, cards, nav) should be quiet and predictable. Surprise lives in the content and in motion — never in the UI shell.

8. **Match the register of the domain.** Borrowing the Linear/Vercel aesthetic for a pet shop, a bakery, or a yoga studio is a tonal mismatch even when every guardrail passes. Dark mode + monochrome = developer tools. Warm light + photography = retail / hospitality / wellness. Read the brief and pick a reference system that fits the *business*, not the one the model defaults to. See `[.cursor/rules/40-tone-and-vertical.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/40-tone-and-vertical.mdc)`.

---

## Layer B — Non-negotiables (the "what")

Hard rules. No exceptions, no creative interpretations.

### Tokens
- Use **only** values from `[.cursor/rules/10-tokens-and-scales.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/10-tokens-and-scales.mdc)`.
- In components, reference **semantic** CSS variables from `[.mba-template/tokens/tokens-modern.css](mdc:.mba-template/tokens/tokens-modern.css)` — `--color-success`, `--color-fg-muted`, `--space-4`. Never the raw palette tokens (`--success-500`, `--neutral-700`) and never the literal values (`oklch(...)`, `#hex`, `rgb(...)`). Palette tokens exist only inside the token file itself.
- Forbidden values: 7px, 13px, 19px, 23px, or any spacing / radius / font-size not in the approved scale.
- One narrow exception: tiny inset UIs inside a hero mockup (phone screen, browser frame, mini-chart) may use `--inset-text-xs/sm/md` and `--inset-radius-sm/md` from `tokens-modern.css`. These exist **only** for "design within a design" and may not be used in the real UI.

#### Where raw color values ARE allowed (and where they are NOT)

Models often "comply" by hoisting all raw values into `:root` and then quietly drop more raw values into selectors anyway. Be explicit:

- ✅ **Allowed** — raw `#hex` / `oklch(...)` / `rgb(...)` inside a `:root { ... }` (or `[data-theme="dark"] { ... }`) block, **only** when defining or overriding the SAME named tokens that exist in `tokens-modern.css` (`--color-bg`, `--color-fg`, `--color-accent`, `--color-success`, `--color-warning`, `--color-danger`, `--color-info`, `--color-border`, etc.). This is theming.
- ❌ **Forbidden** — raw `#hex` / `oklch(...)` / `rgb(...)` inside ANY component selector: `.btn`, `.hero`, `.section-header`, `body`, `h1`, `a:hover`, gradients, `box-shadow`, `linear-gradient(...)` color stops, etc. Always reference a token: `var(--color-bg)`, `var(--color-accent-fg)`, `color-mix(in oklch, var(--color-accent) 80%, black)`.
- ❌ **Forbidden** — `color: #ffffff;` or `color: white;` even if "white" feels like a constant. Use `var(--color-accent-fg)` (or a similar semantic) so the dark/light mode swap stays consistent.
- ❌ **Forbidden** — raw hex inside `linear-gradient(...)`, `radial-gradient(...)`, or `background:` shorthand. If you need a darker version of `--color-bg`, write `color-mix(in oklch, var(--color-bg) 90%, black)`, not `#0a0a0c`.

If you find yourself reaching for a hex value mid-component because "I just need a slightly darker shade here" — that's the signal to (a) add a new semantic token in `:root` and reference it, OR (b) use `color-mix()` against an existing token. Never inline.

### Icons
- **Never generate SVG.** Not `<svg>` markup, not `data:image/svg+xml,...` data URIs in CSS, not base64-encoded SVG. Always use an icon library:
  - Font Awesome: `<i class="fa-solid fa-user" aria-hidden="true"></i>`
  - Heroicons (React): `<UserIcon className="size-5" />`
  - Lucide: `<User size={20} />`
- For chevrons, arrows, and decorative carets in CSS pseudo-elements: use the icon font's unicode (`content: "\f078"; font-family: "Font Awesome 6 Free"; font-weight: 900;`), or place an `<i>` in the markup. Never embed an SVG path.
- See `[.mba-template/ICON-QUICK-REFERENCE.md](mdc:.mba-template/ICON-QUICK-REFERENCE.md)`.

### Avatars (no real photo available)
- For users / authors / testimonials without a real photo: render **initials** in a circle with a deterministic background color derived from the name (`color-mix()` on `--color-accent` with hue rotation, or pick from a small named palette).
- Never use a generic `fa-user`, `fa-user-circle`, silhouette, or default Gravatar as a permanent avatar — that is the textbook AI tell.

### "Logo wall" without real partner logos
- For demo / portfolio pages with no real partners: use **small-caps text wordmarks** in `--color-fg-muted` (e.g. `<span class="logo-wordmark">FETCH&PLAY</span>`), or omit the section. Stock Font Awesome icons posing as company logos (`fa-dog`, `fa-cube`, `fa-rocket`) is the second-most obvious AI tell after the user-icon avatar.

### Content
- **No Lorem ipsum. No "Acme Corp", "John Doe", "user@example.com" defaults.**
- Pull realistic names, emails, companies, and copy from `[.mba-template/content/sample-content.json](mdc:.mba-template/content/sample-content.json)`.
- Numbers are imperfect (`$1,234.56`, `12,847 users`, `+12.4%` — never `$1,000.00`, `10,000`, `+10%`).

### Accessibility (WCAG AA floor)
- Touch targets ≥ 44px × 44px on mobile, ≥ 32px × 32px on desktop.
- Contrast ≥ 4.5:1 for body text, ≥ 3:1 for text 18px+ or bold 14px+.
- Focus outline: 2px solid, 2px offset, uses `:focus-visible` (never the deprecated `:focus`).
- Semantic HTML: `<button>` not `<div onclick>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<article>`, `<aside>`.
- All form inputs have a `<label>`. All icon-only buttons have `aria-label`. Decorative icons are `aria-hidden="true"`.
- Honor `prefers-reduced-motion` for any animation > 200ms or any movement.

### Motion
- Animate only `transform` and `opacity`. Never `width`, `height`, `margin`, `top/left`.
- Durations: 100ms (hover), 200ms (buttons/inputs), 300ms (modals/drawers), 500ms (page transitions).
- Easing: `ease-out` for entrances, `ease-in` for exits, `ease-in-out` for state changes.

### Composition
- One primary action per screen above the fold. Other actions are secondary.
- One density per page (compact / comfortable / spacious — see `[.cursor/rules/50-components.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/50-components.mdc)`).
- Body text left-aligned. Center-align only for short headlines, empty states, and hero copy.
- Maximum 2–3 accent colors. Plus one neutral scale and 4 semantic colors (success/warning/error/info).
- A "primary + secondary" pair must be **visually distinct**, not the same size + same icon style + adjacent. The secondary is one or more of: ghost variant, smaller size, no icon, or a plain text link.

### Vertical fit (read the room)
- The visual register must match the business. A pet shop should not feel like a fintech dashboard; a law firm should not feel like a children's book; a restaurant should not feel like a CLI tool.
- Before generating, consult `[.cursor/rules/40-tone-and-vertical.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/40-tone-and-vertical.mdc)` to pick the right reference system, light/dark default, and whether real photography is mandatory for this vertical.

